# CI Guards, Security Controls, and Sovereign Security Infrastructure

## Why this exists
This note translates the repo's current security posture into plain English and then ties it back to the sovereign architecture already living inside the platform. The goal is to make the current controls understandable, name the custom systems already present, and show where they fit together.

---

## 1. CI and policy gates already in place

### Build, package and test
The main pull-request pipeline is the GitHub Actions workflow named **`Build, package and test`**. It runs on pull requests to `master`, on pushes to `master`, on manual dispatch, and on a nightly schedule. Inside that workflow, the first explicit security policy step is **`Policy Gate - Disallowed AI Provider Signatures`**, which runs `node scripts/check-disallowed-ai-providers.js`. In plain English: every PR can be scanned for banned AI provider signatures before the rest of the install/build/test stack runs, so a leak gets caught in CI instead of after merge. This is exactly the kind of “automatic PR block until fixed” control you described. The same workflow also enforces linting, packaging, and platform tests, which means security policy and software integrity are already tied together instead of being treated as separate concerns.

### Release-gate layer
SuperIDE also has a second gate model in its release tooling. The release gate evaluator groups checks into `security`, `reliability`, `data_integrity`, and `executive_readiness`, and the `security` lane explicitly requires `gateway_only`, `provider_strings`, `secure_defaults`, `external_endpoints`, and `protected_apps`. The `data_integrity` lane already includes `.skye`-related integrity checks through `skye_schema` and `export_import_schema`. That matters because it means the repo is not only checking “does it build?” but also “did the security boundary remain intact?” and “did the secure data format stay valid?”.

### `.skye` validation visible in release planning
The release-gates documentation explicitly says `.skye` validation must remain visible through canonical contract validity, secure roundtrip retention, tamper rejection, and passphrase enforcement. So the repo already treats `.skye` as a governed format, not a loose export convenience.

